3ï¸âƒ£ I once believed that futures and leverage would amplify the weaknesses of human nature, and I adamantly swore we'd never do it. That is, until the bear market of 2019 when all coins were crashing and users everywhere were in agony. I crammed on financial knowledge, learned about hedging, and later forced two futures teams to compete against each other. But we never forgot to make users pass a test before trading futures, nor did we forget to implement a cooling-off period for users who were constantly going all-in. I have myself to thank for the moments I've had to eat my own words.
I once believed that MEMEs were just conspiracy-driven schemes disguised as subculture, and that the only righteous path was for legitimate projects to be responsible for their holders. That is, until I saw those projects with squeaky-clean, respectable-looking founders, who talked a big game about dreams and passion, only use Binance as their final liquidity exit to dump on everyone. Retail users are defenseless against these professional players; they get dumped on in the spot market or liquidated in futures. I understand their anger, but I felt powerless to change the structural problems in the industry. I once choked up during a 6-hour AMA because I didn't know how both retail and professional players could win. What if we wanted our users to be the first stop? That was the beginning of finding Alpha.
Eventually, I made peace with myself. Most users aren't looking for guaranteed profits. What users want is fairness, fairness, and goddamn fairness. They aren't speculating on "#BinanceLife" or "#CustomerServiceXiaoHe"; they are looking for that small grain of fairness, opportunity, and consensus that accumulates under these contract addresses. At this point, I should probably also give an unwelcome reminder: for MEMEs, no one is responsible for the project, there is no long-term value backing them, and there are plenty of malicious groups involved. Be aware of the investment risks. A contract address containing "Binance" or my name, or a tweet, does not constitute an endorsement from Binance or me.
